 group and have students try to prove it]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assume for contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a ratio of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

.
 And let's say this fraction is in lowest terms, meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 share no common factors that we could cancel, in other words 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(a,b)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Well, let's play around with the resulting equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}=\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

.
 We don't yet know much about 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, so let's square both sides:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2=\frac{a^{2}}{b^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Equations involving fractions are not as nice as equations without them,
 so let's multiply both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2b^{2}=a^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
All this tells us is that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even.
 What does this mean? This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 must be even.
 [Why? We'll fill in this gap in a second.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is even, what else do we know? Well, remember we're trying to contradict
 our assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}=\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
in lowest terms
\series default
.
 We don't seem to have a way to contradict that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}=\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 directly, but what about the lowest terms part? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is even, say 
\begin_inset Formula $a=2k$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}=4k^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}$
\end_inset

 is actually divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
But if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}=4k^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a^{2}}{b^{2}}=2$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}=2k^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even as well!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 must be even as well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
But if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are both even, then we can cancel a 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 from top and bottom of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

, contradicting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 is in lowest terms!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Therefore, our initial assumption was false, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 is not a rational number.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
You're lucky you live in a time where this proof won't get you thrown off
 a ship!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Incidentally, standard printer paper is designed to have a common ratio
 between the two edges even when we fold the paper in half (for scaling).
 It turns out that the only way to do this is to make at least one of the
 sides of the paper have length an irrational number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
[in groups] Prove by contradiction that, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 must be even as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assume for contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is not even.
 Then it's odd, so 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2n+1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a whole number.
 But then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p^{2}=(2n+1)^{2}=4n^{2}+4n+1.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $4n^{2}+4n$
\end_inset

 is clearly even, 
\begin_inset Formula $4n^{2}+4n+1$
\end_inset

 must be odd.
 This is a contradiction of our original assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even! Since the only thing we assumed for contradiction was that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 was not even, that original assumption must be wrong.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is even!
\end_layout

